BEGIN:VEVENT
DTSTART:20260323T200000Z
DTEND:20260323T210000Z
LOCATION:Hamilton Lugar School - Room Number: 1060
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Paulo Ramos
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Paulo Ramos\, former postdoc at the Center for Research on Race 
 &amp\; Ethnicity in Society\, current visiting scholar of Ostrom Workshop
 .  Paulo's research project Bodies of Water ("Corpos d'Ăˇgua") explores e
 nvironmental racism and Black women's relationships to water. Part of his
  work offers artistic performance that delves into conceptual realms thro
 ugh poetry and corporeal expression\, and he has published a volume of po
 etry also entitled Bodies of Water. Paulo's performance invites a sensory
  experience while reflecting on environmental racism and transcending rac
 ial and class boundaries. Focusing on the connection between water and Bl
 ack women\, Paulo's work highlights the draining of dreams and lives from
  Black bodies by the state\, a situation that dates back to colonial Braz
 il. The situation Paulo examines constitutes an ongoing cycle of violence
  deeply rooted in the legacy of slavery and entrenched within institution
 al frameworks.  Abstract: PhD dissertation Bodies of Water: etnographY of
  Black Poetics of Feeling-Doing (2025) is a multidisciplinary work that c
 ombines art\, literature\, and anthropology of the senses and images tran
 sformed into emotions. Corpos d'Ăˇgua is about Paulo's mother\, grandmoth
 er\, and aunt and the relationship these Black women had with the waters 
 of the Bahia River\, an aquatic current between the river\, the mangrove\
 , and the sea which becomes the Atlantic Ocean. The work-research analyze
 s these geographies as spaces of escape\, freedom\, and energy connected 
 to Black women mothers. Paul's art is a meditation on water and Black wom
 en in literature and art as a diasporic force that\, even though traverse
 d by the rupture and violence of colonialism\, does not erase ancestry or
  Black life.  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from Februar
 y through April\, with faculty and guest speakers engaging Latin America 
 and the Caribbean through research on history\, culture\, language\, poli
 tics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (https://events.iu.edu/clac
 s/) for details.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Paulo Ramo
 s</strong>\, former postdoc at the Center for Research on Race &amp\; Eth
 nicity in Society\, current visiting scholar of Ostrom Workshop.</p><p><b
 r />  Paulo's research project Bodies of Water ("Corpos d'Ăˇgua") explore
 s environmental racism and Black women's relationships to water. Part of 
 his work offers artistic performance that delves into conceptual realms t
 hrough poetry and corporeal expression\, and he has published a volume of
  poetry also entitled Bodies of Water. Paulo's performance invites a sens
 ory experience while reflecting on environmental racism and transcending 
 racial and class boundaries. Focusing on the connection between water and
  Black women\, Paulo's work highlights the draining of dreams and lives f
 rom Black bodies by the state\, a situation that dates back to colonial B
 razil. The situation Paulo examines constitutes an ongoing cycle of viole
 nce deeply rooted in the legacy of slavery and entrenched within institut
 ional frameworks.</p><p>  Abstract: <span class="a_GcMg font-feature-liga
 -off font-feature-clig-off font-feature-calt-off text-decoration-none tex
 t-strikethrough-none" style="color: rgba(0\,0\,0\,var(--o42jjq\,1))\; car
 et-color: #000000\; --ys-xuq: none\; font-style: normal\; font-kerning: n
 ormal\;">PhD dissertation <em>Bodies of Water: etnographY of Black Poetic
 s of Feeling-Doing</em> (2025) is a multidisciplinary work that combines 
 art\, literature\, and anthropology of the senses and images transformed 
 into emotions. Corpos d'Ăˇgua is about Paulo's mother\, grandmother\, and
  aunt and the relationship these Black women had with the waters of the B
 ahia River\, an aquatic current between the river\, the mangrove\, and th
 e sea which becomes the Atlantic Ocean. The work-research analyzes these 
 geographies as spaces of escape\, freedom\, and energy connected to Black
  women mothers. Paul's art is a meditation on water and Black women in li
 terature and art as a diasporic force that\, even though traversed by the
  rupture and violence of colonialism\, does not erase ancestry or Black l
 ife.</span></p><p>  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from F
