LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 0001
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Elena GuzmĂˇn\, Beatrice Capot
 e\, Solimar Otero\, Maria Hamilton Abegunde
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Elena GuzmĂˇn\, Beatrice Capote\, Solimar Otero\, and Maria Hami
 lton Abegunde as they present OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun.OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun is an experimen
 tal short film that honors the Orisha Oshun\, a central figure in Yoruba 
 cosmology and spirituality. Rooted in the Yoruba tradition of orĂ­kĂ¬â€”a
  performative act of praise that invokes the essence\, attributes\, and d
 estiny of a person\, place\, or deityâ€”this film reimagines the possibil
 ities of storytelling through a multisensory\, synesthetic cinematic expe
 rience. Through a series of interconnected vignettes\, OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun weav
 es together sacred stories (pataki) that reveal the multidimensionality o
 f Oshun. While often celebrated as the Orisha of beauty\, love\, and weal
 th\, this film ventures beyond these familiar portrayals\, offering a dee
 per and more complex vision of Oshun's identity. It explores her sacrific
 es\, her struggles\, her resilience\, and her transformation into a fierc
 e warrior. By blending traditional Yoruba performance aesthetics with exp
 erimental film techniques\, OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun creates a polyrhythmic and imme
 rsive space where sound\, image\, and movement converge to honor the sacr
 ed. This project is not just a celebration of Oshun but a meditation on t
 he power of storytelling to expand our understanding of divine multiplici
 ty\, human imperfection\, and sacred possibility.  &#160\;  The CLACS Spr
 ing 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from February through April\, with facu
 lty and guest speakers engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through r
 esearch on history\, culture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check 
 the CLACS Calendar (https://events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Elena Guzm
 Ăˇn\, Beatrice Capote\, Solimar Otero\, and Maria Hamilton Abegunde</stro
 ng> as they present <strong><em>OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun.</em></strong></p><p><stron
 g><em>OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun</em></strong> is an experimental short film that hono
 rs the Orisha <em>Oshun</em>\, a central figure in Yoruba cosmology and s
 pirituality. Rooted in the Yoruba tradition of orĂ­kĂ¬â€”a performative a
 ct of praise that invokes the essence\, attributes\, and destiny of a per
 son\, place\, or deityâ€”this film reimagines the possibilities of storyt
 elling through a multisensory\, synesthetic cinematic experience. Through
  a series of interconnected vignettes\, <strong><em>OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun</em></s
 trong> weaves together sacred stories (pataki) that reveal the multidimen
 sionality of Oshun. While often celebrated as the Orisha of beauty\, love
 \, and wealth\, this film ventures beyond these familiar portrayals\, off
 ering a deeper and more complex vision of Oshun's identity. It explores h
 er sacrifices\, her struggles\, her resilience\, and her transformation i
 nto a fierce warrior. By blending traditional Yoruba performance aestheti
 cs with experimental film techniques\, <strong><em>OrĂ­kĂ¬ Oshun</em></st
 rong> creates a polyrhythmic and immersive space where sound\, image\, an
 d movement converge to honor the sacred. This project is not just a celeb
 ration of Oshun but a meditation on the power of storytelling to expand o
 ur understanding of divine multiplicity\, human imperfection\, and sacred
  possibility.</p><p><picture class="lw_image lw_image29945  lw_align_left
